@zcassini I thought about what you said. I don't fully agree with what you said - while a chef provisioner has indeed undergone tests from different angles, it's meant for industry standard provisioning (like, in an org at an MNC, you want to provision 50 CentOS boxes - you are probably better off with Chef or Puppet. The IT dept, and DevOps team can handle the bandwidth and time spent on that).

But it is probably not meant for someone who has a personal laptop or a family desktop. Especially if I have to install 130 MB plugins and dev kits manually.

**However, in the end, it doesn't matter**; because the end user would get the fully provisioned box. They would be abstracted away from the layer of provisioning activity. It's only a problem for the tester, especially on Windows with low RAM, like 4 GB. The Windows bash is going to be slow enough - which is not a true bash.

